1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1170":"1170","Fearn, Ross-shire, Scotland":"Fearn, Ross-shire, Scotland","Alba":"Alba, Romania","Tain, Alba":"Tain, Highland, Scotland, United Kingdom","Applecross, Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Applecross, Ross and Cromarty, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacGillvray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McGillivray  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McGillivray","meanings":["Scottish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Gille Bhràtha</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (God's) Judgment’.","variant of   McElrath  , from <b>Mac Gille Riabhaigh</b>."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret MacGillvray was born in 1178, her father, William MacGillvrey, was 30 and her mother, Heth Nic Aead, was 23. She married Fearchar of Ross about 1194, in Alba, Romania. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in Tain, Highland, Scotland, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1178–":"1178–Surnud","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1170–1251":"1170–1251","1213–Female":"1213–Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1220–1274":"1220–1274","1148–1210":"1148–1210","1155–1178":"1155–1178","about 1194":"umbes 1194","1215":"1215","1148":"1148","1213":"1213","1178":"1178","about 1215":"umbes 1215","1155":"1155","1210":"1210","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1251":"1251","1170":"1170","Fearn, Ross-shire, Scotland":"Fearn, Ross-shire, Scotland","Alba":"Alba, Rumeenia","Tain, Alba":"Tain, Highland, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Applecross, Cromartyshire, Scotland":"Applecross, Ross and Cromarty, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1178–":"1178–Kuo